body:
### Component

Forge

### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?

- [X] Foundry
- [X] Foundryup

### What version of Foundry are you on?

forge 0.2.0 (a0a31c3 2023-08-12T00:23:12.943797000Z)

### What command(s) is the bug in?

forge script

### Operating System

macOS (Apple Silicon)

### Describe the bug

```solidity
contract NonceBug is Script {
    function run() public payable {
        vm.broadcast(1);
        IERC20(0xA0b86991c6218b36c1d19D4a2e9Eb0cE3606eB48).approve(
            address(1), 1000
        );

        vm.broadcast(1);
        IERC20(0xA0b86991c6218b36c1d19D4a2e9Eb0cE3606eB48).approve(
            address(1), 1000
        );
    }
}
```
Dry-running following script on mainnet will generate two transactions with the same nonce for the same sender:
```
{
  "transactions": [
    {
        ...
        "nonce": "0x661",
        "accessList": []
      },
      ...
    },
    {
        ...
        "nonce": "0x661",
        "accessList": []
      },
      ...
    }
  ],
...
}
```

When adding --broadcast flag, script will fail with error `EOA nonce changed unexpectedly while sending transactions`

I have tracked the issue down to this line of code: https://github.com/foundry-rs/foundry/blob/410c8173e76b9fa42864e2d63309cd7cc4b6cfd9/crates/evm/src/executor/inspector/cheatcodes/mod.rs#L727
And it seems to be actually increasing nonce to correct next value. But somehow on the next broadcast it becomes the old value again.

Another interesting thing here is that following script would generate correct nonces:
```solidity
contract NonceBug is Script {
    function run() public payable {
        vm.broadcast(1);
        address(0).call("");

        vm.broadcast(1);
        address(0).call("");
    }
}

```
```
{
  "transactions": [
    {
        ...
        "nonce": "0x661",
        "accessList": []
      },
      ...
    },
    {
        ...
        "nonce": "0x662",
        "accessList": []
      },
      ...
    }
  ],
...
}
```

Also, using `vm.startBroadcast()/vm.stopBroadcast()` instead of `vm.broadcast()` solves the issue too.
